post_text:
Due to the continued hazardous air quality both outside and inside our school buildings, the Mead School District has cancelled school for Monday, Sept. 14, for all students - virtual, hybrid and in-person. In operating on a district-wide calendar that all students adhere to, delivering virtual classes and not in-person would push the calendar out of balance. Cancelling virtual classes also helps maintain the health and safety of many of our teachers who have chosen to deliver virtual classes from our buildings.

More information on chromebook pickup here: https://bit.ly/33ndM6t

post_text: For those of you who selected remote online learning for your elementary child this school year, we want you to know how excited we are to welcome you to this new online learning environment. We would like to announce that Chris Backman has been assigned as the principal responsible for elementary online learning during this time -- taking a leave from his regular duties as Meadow Ridge Elementary principal. He is a great leader and ready to work alongside all of you in delivering the best learning experience possible. Chris and his team have been working tirelessly to enroll more than 1,000 students in this new program. You will receive a welcome message today via email with more information for your family. Thank you for your continued support and patience as we create an excellent online learning environment for each student.
text: For those of you who selected remote online learning for your elementary child this school year, we want you to know how excited we are to welcome you to this new online learning environment. He is a great leader and ready to work alongside all of you in delivering the best learning experience possible. Chris and his team have been working tirelessly to enroll more than 1,000 students in this new program. You will receive a welcome message today via email with more information for your family. Thank you for your continued support and patience as we create an excellent online learning environment for each student.

post_text:
ACT SIX SCHOLAR: Act Six is a leadership/scholarship program for emerging urban and community leaders. Mt. Spokane's Noor Kamal, who graduated with a 3.83 GPA, earned an ACT 6 scholarship at Whitworth University, where he will attend in the fall.

Noor left home at age 14 with the blessing of his mother and boarded a boat to escape the genocide happening to Rohingya people in Myranmar. After a harrowing voyage, followed by time in a refugee camp, Noor came to Spokane in April 2017. We congratulate Noor on all of his accomplishments!
text:
ACT SIX SCHOLAR: Act Six is a leadership/scholarship program for emerging urban and community leaders. Mt. Spokane's Noor Kamal, who graduated with a 3.83 GPA, earned an ACT 6 scholarship at Whitworth University, where he will attend in the fall.

Noor left home at age 14 with the blessing of his mother and boarded a boat to escape the genocide happening to Rohingya people in Myranmar. After a harrowing voyage, followed by time in a refugee camp, Noor came to Spokane in April 2017. We congratulate Noor on all of his accomplishments!

APPRECIATION: Several weeks ago we shared an episode of "Mr. Danford Shares" on our Facebook feed. Today we are sharing the final episode on the subject of appreciation. While Mr. Danford is speaking specifically to Evergreen students, teachers, staff and parents, the words of appreciation expressed can be applied to each of our school communities.

Starting in mid-March and continuing throughout the entirety of this spring's Emergency School Closure, Mike Danford, Evergreen Principal, starred in and produced 61 episodes of "Mr. Dandord Shares" . . . all are available to view on YouTube.

post_text: MEAD EATS SUMMER SCHEDULE: Our FREE Mead Eats program will continue into the summer using a modified model that includes three school locations (Brentwood, Evergreen & Shiloh Hills) plus two community locations (Deer Run Apartments & North Spokane Library). The last day of our current MEAD EATS service will be Wednesday, June 17. The modified MEAD EATS model will begin on Monday, June 22 and run through August 20 (Monday-Thursday). Click the link for additional information & distribution times. https://www.mead354.org/apps/news/article/1191804

FINALISTS ANNOUNCED: An impressive eight Mt. Spokane athletes/teams are 2020 Spokane Youth Sports Awards Finalists! Nominees include: Travis Hughes (Wrestling) Coach of the Year, Dave Whitehead (Volleyball) Coach of the Year, Mt. Spokane Volleyball (Top Female Team of the Year), Mt. Spokane Wrestling (Top Male Team of the Year), Tia Allen (Volleyball & Basketball) Female Athlete of the Year, Kannon Katzer (Football) Male Athlete of the Year, Cheyenne King (Figure Skating) Non-High School Sports Top Female Athlete and Jose-Alvarez-Renteria (Football/Baseball) Against All Odds Honoree.

SWX will air the awards ceremony on Friday, June 26 @ 7 pm.

Midway Seniors 2020

Midway Elementary School
June 3 at 6:56 PM ¬∑

We are so excited to welcome back our graduating seniors who attended Midway! They will be driving through the Midway parking lot tomorrow morning so our staff can bid them farewell. Here's a video of some of their final Midway moments. Enjoy!

post_text: GREAT PICTURES from Evergreen Elementary where last Thursday (June 4) teachers welcomed Class of 2020 alumni back to celebrate their high school graduation. Celebrations like this took place last Thursday throughout the district at all of our elementary school locations.
shared_text:
Evergreen Elementary
June 4 at 5:02 PM ¬∑

What a special morning. The Evergreen staff turned out! I'll tell you what‚Äîpast and present.

Although a different time and a different protocol, we still celebrated our Mead High seniors, those formally of Evergreen Elementary School.

They came by, honked, and allowed staff to cheer and celebrate with them. We offered the high schoolers a treat and a "glass" of milk...all while social distancing and/or wearing PPE of course.

Go Panthers!

post_text:
NEW STADIUM: Following community input, we are pleased to announce the name of the facility will be Union Stadium. This name encompasses the site's past as well as its future. The stadium is being built on the Mead Consolidated Union High School site that opened in 1911 (SW corner of Market & Farwell in the town of Mead).

Union High School eventually became Mead High School, then Mead Junior High School and ultimately Mead Middle School. Regarding the future, this venue will be a community gathering place that will unify the Mead School District for generations to come.

NAME OUR NEW STADIUM: Thanks to all who participated in earlier surveys to help us name our new stadium located on the SW corner of Farwell & Market in the town of Mead. The building of this stadium was approved by voters in February 2018 and, beginning in the fall, this new facility will host home football games and soccer matches, as well as Marching Band activities and competitions, for both Mt. Spokane and Mead High.

We've narrowed the name for the new venue down to the following three options: Market Street Stadium - Bell Stadium - Union Stadium

Click the link provided to vote for your favorite. The survey closes May 17 @ midnight. https://forms.gle/MZ4fBw3BcFABrWDQ7

post_text:
MT. SPOKANE HIGH SCHOOL - 3A SCHOLASTIC CUP CHAMPION: Congratulations to Mt. Spokane High School on earning this year's 3A WIAA Scholastic Cup - the very first in school history. The Scholastic Cup is the WIAA's most prestigious annual school award. It recognizes the top school in each of the six WIAA classifications based on academic, athletic and sportsmanship excellence.

The Wildcats finished with 1,200 points, the most of any school among the six WIAA classifications.

post_text: UPDATE FROM THE COLLEGE BOARD for our AP students.
shared_text:
The College Board
March 16 at 11:26 AM ¬∑

The College Board is developing tools to mitigate the impact of school closures on students in the Advanced Placement Program. All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. We‚Äôre working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit they‚Äôve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Board‚Äôs focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

SCHOOL CLOSURE ANNOUNCEMENT: Following Governor Inslee's Emergency Declaration this afternoon, all Mead School District Schools will be closed for students starting Tuesday, March 17 through at least April 24, 2020, in an effort to aggressively slow the spread of COVID-19.

All schools will be open Monday, March 16, as a transition day for staff and families to adjust to the closure. We respect any family who chooses to keep their child at home on Monday. Parents, students and families can also retrieve medications and other essential personal items Monday.

This prolonged closure will impact every aspect of our district and our region. Please know we are working to get you up-to-date information and will continue to be in regular contact via our website and social media as soon as we have more information to share.

SCHOOL CLOSURE ANNOUNCEMENT: Following Governor Inslee's Emergency Declaration this afternoon, all Mead School District Schools will be closed for students starting Tuesday, March 17 through at least April 24, 2020, in an effort to aggressively slow the spread of COVID-19.

All schools will be open Monday, March 16, as a transition day for staff and families to adjust to the closure. We respect any family who chooses to keep their child at home on Monday. Parents, students and families can also retrieve medications and other essential personal items Monday.

This prolonged closure will impact every aspect of our district and our region. Please know we are working to get you up-to-date information and will continue to be in regular contact via our website and social media as soon as we have more information to share.

post_text: 5 NEW BREAKFAST ENTREES: The theme for National School Breakfast Week (March 2-6) is "School Breakfast Out of this World." All of our elementary schools will be participating by serving five new, never before offered, entrees. On Monday, March 2 (Dr. Seuss Day) we will be serving a special version of Green Eggs & Ham. The following four days the entrees will be "space themed" and include Asteroid Pancake Bites, Flying Saucer Breakfast Sandwich, Intergalactic Smoothie and Berries & Cream Fuel Cell.

This piece of memorabilia is now hanging in the foyer of our Maintenance Facility (12510 N. Market) and is visible from the road at night.

Monte is pictured (3rd from the left) with members of our Maintenance staff.

post_text: BACK-TO-BACK-TO-BACK STATE CHAMPIONS: In what is shaping up to be a dynasty, Mt. Spokane is once again this year the 3A State Wrestling Champion! Congratulations to Head Coach Travis Hughes and the entire team, which includes two 3A Individual State Champions (Ky Haney - #145 & Casey Howerton - #152), and two 3A Academic State Champions (Riley Buth & Jacob Carr) who are both 4.0 GPA students.

MILLION STEPS CHALLENGE: The first week of February, over the course of four days, Mead School District employees from nearly every school and building site, participated in the American Heart Association's Million Steps Challenge. Mt. Spokane HS logged the most steps (2,154,028) and the total for the district was 14,125,565!

Heart failure affects nearly six million Americans and a new case is diagnosed every 35 seconds.

COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT MEETING: Last evening at Mt. Spokane High School 40 community members joined Superintendent Shawn Woodward at the first of two Community Engagement Meetings. (The second Community Engagement Meeting is this Thursday, February 6, 6:30 pm at Mead High School.) The following questions were considered: What is the district doing well? What areas need immediate attention? What are your hopes, dreams and aspirations for the district in the future?

The district is in the process of developing a five-year Strategic Plan and the information gathered from the community will be instrumental in informing the priorities of the Mead School District moving forward.

post_text: MEAD HIGH SCHOOL ATHLETIC HALL OF FAME: On Thursday, February 6th, during halftime of the Girls Basketball Game (5:30 pm tip) Mead High School will host the Inaugural Induction into the school's Athletic Hall of Fame. 2020 Inductees are Becky (Nelson) Clark (Class of 1968) who, still to this day, holds the Mead High School high jump record (5'8") and Gary Baskett who served as the Mead High Head Boys Track & Field Coach for 20 years, winning five state championships.

THANKS & APPRECIATION: January is "School Board Appreciation Month" in the state of Washington. To help extend a well-deserved THANK YOU to our school board, current and newly elected ASB officers from both Mead High and Mt. Spokane were in attendance at Monday's school board meeting where Superintendent Woodward read a Proclamation signed by Governor Jay Inslee extolling the dedication of those who serve as members of local school boards.

The Mead School District Board of Directors includes Carmen Green (President), Chad Burchard (Vice-President), Bob Olson, Denny Denholm & Michael Cannon.

post_text:
MEAD HIGH AP LANGUAGE TEACHER HONORED: At this past Monday's School Board Meeting Olinda Martin was recognized by Principal Jeff Naslund for her steadfast commitment to fostering a culture of "belonging" at Mead High School. According to Mr. Naslund, Olinda is a "rock star." Ms. Martin teaches five sections of AP Language and also serves as the advisor for the "Dungeons & Dragons" club where 30+ students gather after school two days each week.

Joining Mr. Naslund for this special school board recognition were students Caleb Kingsford and Jack Dean who spoke eloquently about the positive impact Ms. Martin has had on them personally.

FARWELL'S CARMEL ADAMS HONORED: A new, reoccurring agenda item at School Board meetings is the opportunity for each school, on an assigned night, to recognize the accomplishments of staff and students.

At the most recent November 18th meeting Farwell Principal Josh VanCleef recognized 5th grade teacher Carmel Adams. Last year Carmel's students had the highest science scores in the entire school district . . . a testimony to Carmel's dedication and hard work in providing the very best learning environment for her students.

post_text: LOVE this Brentwood tradition of giving back to community during the Holiday Season.
shared_text:
Brentwood Elementary
November 14, 2019 at 10:34 AM ¬∑

At Brentwood we have a lasting tradition to meet the needs of our families by our Tree of Sharing. The tree has been put up in our office with requests for gifts, clothing and/or grocery/gas gift cards. Simply grab a tag from the tree and sign up on the sheet provided. We would like to have gifts returned to us by no later than Friday, December 11th. We are hopeful that we can help every family who has asked and we would not be able to do it without the generosity of this incredible community!

TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT FOOD DRIVE: The annual "Fill the Bus" Food Drive, organized and sponsored by our Transportation Department, collected an impressive 1,100 lbs. of food plus $3,322.90 in cash, at two locations last Saturday. Food and money have been donated to the Mead Food Bank.

In addition to thanking the community for their generosity we also acknowledge and thank Fred Meyer and Yokes Fresh Market plus the following Transportation staff volunteers: Chris Covell, Warren Daubel, Majdolin Haddad, Dan Fisher, Linda Skiles, Cheryl Bostwick & Josias, Shelly Doyle & family including Holly the dog, Mike Wallace, John Fisher, Laura Boyle, Tim Madsen, Stephanie Charles, David Villa, Larry Helmer, Stan LaMotte, Pam Allen, Larry & Cindy Tennant, Lisa Cole, Elaine Willis, Lauri Penaluna, Carol Lowman, Anthony Falwey, Henk Borst, Karen Zeller and Jeff Rabel.

NOVEMBER 5 SUPPLEMENTAL LEVY BALLOT MEASURE: What percentage of property taxes goes to the Mead School District? For a home with an assessed value of $240,000, the graphs provide a breakdown of where property tax dollars are allocated. The PROPOSED graph includes an increase in school district taxes of $20/month ($1/$1,000 of assessed value) and assumes no change in other line items.

For comparison purposes, for the CURRENT 2019 collection year, the percentage of property taxes going to Spokane Schools was 35% compared to 29% for the Mead School District. The PROPOSED Mead percentage is 34.5%. Click the link to learn more about this ballot measure. https://www.mead354.org/apps/pages/Safety_Security_Wellness_Levy/
